  "prompt": "What is the difference between liking vs loving someone?",
  "response": "The difference between liking and loving someone can be quite nuanced, but here are some key distinctions:\n\nLiking Someone:\n1. Surface-level attraction\n2. Enjoying someone's company\n3. Appreciation of their qualities\n4. Relatively shallow emotional connection\n5. Less commitment\n6. More about what they can do for you\n7. Easier to walk away from\n\nLoving Someone:\n1. Deep emotional attachment\n2. Unconditional care and support\n3. Willingness to sacrifice for their happiness\n4. Strong emotional investment\n5. Commitment and loyalty\n6. Acceptance of their flaws\n7. Desire for their well-being, even at personal cost\n8. More profound and complex emotional connection\n9. Long-term perspective\n10. Includes elements of friendship, intimacy, and trust\n\nRomantic love typically involves:\n- Physical and emotional attraction\n- Intimacy\n- Passion\n- Commitment\n\nPlatonic love (like with family/friends) involves:\n- Deep care\n- Mutual respect\n- Supportiveness\n- Acceptance\n\nEssentially, loving is a much deeper, more comprehensive emotional experience compared to simply liking someone.",
